In Java, the == operator compares the memory addresses of the two objects, while the .equals() method compares the contents of the two objects. This means that == will always return false if the two objects refer to different locations in memory, while .equals() will only return false if the two objects have different values.

For example, consider the following code:

String s1 = "hello";
String s2 = "hello";

if (s1 == s2) {
